# @COMMENT: According to HMXXV01P029B HishaAm b. IshaCIl b. HishAm b. al-WalId b. al-WalId b. MughIrah was the father inlaw of ʿAbd al-MAlik b. MarwAn and the grandfather of HishAm b. ʿAbd al-MAlik by his daught FATimah. HishaAm b. IshaCIl led the pilgrimage in 87/706 by the order of ʿAbd al-MAlik (HMXXV01P025C). SFTXV01P289B states that he also led the pigrimage in 83/702, 84/703 (SFTXV01P290A), 85/704 (SFTXV01P291A). He was appointed governor of MadInah in 83/704 and remained in that position unit ʿAbd al-MAlik's death that following year(SFTXV01P293A). Placement is approximate based on the year of his appointment as governor over MadInah.

### || سنة أربع ومائة

# @ZTTHV01P194A_BEG_WSACD حدثنا أبي قال حدثنا @TR2_YISI@ يعقوب بن إبراهيم بن سعد قال حدثنا @TR1_SACD@ أبي عن ابن إسحاق قال وحدثني عبد الله بن أبي نجيح ... ابن سويد الباهلي قال حدثنا حميد الأعرج قال كنت مع مجاهد فقال له رجل يا أبا الحجاج. @ZTTHV01P194A_END_WSACD
PageV01P194
# @COMMENT: Passage not found in the redaction of Ibn Hishām. Quotation comes from a section that focuses on Mujāhid b. Jabr, who was a regular source cited by Ibn Isḥāq. According to TKXXV06P019A, his kunyā was Abū al-Ḥajjāj, and he died in 104/722. The fragment is quoted to establish his kunyā. Ḥumayd al-Aʿraj, also known as ̣Ḥumayd b. Qays al-Aʿraj was a mawlā of the Zubayr b. ʿAwwām family. He was a Meccan and was a specialist in Qurʾānic recitation (TKXXV06P034G). According to BNTHV06P189D, he died in Mecca in 130/747. He does not appear as a source for Ibn Isḥāq except for this passage. There are several possibilities for placement, the most likely given the structure of the text, is in the year Mujāhid b. Jabr died.

### ||| لذين ماتوا أثناء خلافة عمر ين عبد العزيز (99-101ح)

# @ZTTHV02P177A_BEG_WSACD
VAR_RZJXV09P294C حدثنا أبي قال حدثنا @TR2_YISI@ يعقوب بن إبراهيم بن سعد قال حدثنا @TR1_SACD@ أبي عن ابن إسحاق قال قال ابن شهاب وحدثني يزيد بن هرمز وكان يزيد من الثقات. @ZTTHV02P177A_END_WSACD
PageV02P177
# @COMMENT: This fragment is an assessment passage referring to Yazīd b. Hurmuz, who was also known as Yazīd al-Fārisī (TMSMV01P233B) and as a mawlā of the banū Layth. According to TKXXV07P164D, Yazīd b. Hurmuz was the commander of the manumitted slaves (mawālī) at the yawm al-Ḥarah (Battle of the Camel), where he appears to have been associated with ʿUthmān's side (BKHBV08P368A). He is often listed as the scribe for ʿAbd Allāh b. ʿAbbās (see the many passages listed below in which he writes Ibn ʿAbbās' reply to Najdah al-Ḥarūr). He is also listed as a scribe for ʿUbayd Allāh b. Ziyād (Ibid). He died during the Caliphate of ʿUmar b. ʿAbd al-ʿAzīz (c. 99/717 to 101/720--see BNTHV05P532A).He is not listed by either name in the redaction of Ibn Hishām. This assessment passage is not located elsewhere in the corpus. @EC_02/28/23@ Yazīd b. Hurmuz is listed in the isnād for a fragment that deals with the role of women in battle during the raids of the prophet in WASMR, WAKMW, WMSAH, and WHAYA. @EC_02/28/23@ Also see the tradition that recounts how ʿUmar b. al-Khaṭṭāb distribute charity during the Year of the Drought (Ramādah), which occurred in the year 18 during a major drought (see SFTXV01P138C). Also see WBSAB, WABAW, WAKMW, and WSFAB for a reference to the event. @EC_02/28/23@ Also see WHAYA and WASMR for a fragment describing how Najdah al-Ḥarūrī wrote Ibn ʿAbbās about inheritance rules. @EC_02/28/23@ The fragment is similar to the type of statement made in a death notice. Placement is provisional, based on his date of death. @EC_02/28/23@

