# @BKHBV04P044C_BEG_WSACD
VAR_RWTXV02P903A VAR_AKHSV04P151A VAR_STBXV06P044A VAR_NYMXV03P1281A VAR_THRXV02P448A قال لي حمزة نا عبد العزيز بن محمد عن عبيد الله بن عمر عن عبد الوهاب بن بخت عن سليمان بن خبيب أن سعد بن عمارة لما حضر قال لابنه وقال لي عمرو بن محمد PageV04P044 نا @TR2_YISI@ يعقوب بن إبراهيم نا عن ابن إسحاق حدثني عبد الله بن أبي بكر ابن محمد بن عمرو بن حزم ويحيى بن سعيد بن قيس عن سعد بن عبادة أحد بني سعد بن بكر له صحبة وسابقة وقال لي عبيد نا @TR1_YBWS@ يونس عن ابن إسحاق عن عبد الله بن أبي بكر عن سعد بن عمارة وله صحبة أسبغ الوضوء والأول أصح @BKHBV04P044C_END_WSACD
PageV04P045
# @COMMENT: The isnād drops WSACD between Yaʿqūb b. Ibrāhīm and Ibn Isḥāq. Passage is not found in the redaction of Ibn Hishām. The tradition can also be found in a trucated form (as with BKHBV04P044C) in WYBWS. The passage focuses on a kind of homily about ablution, faith, and prayer. The original witness for the tradition in this complex is given four naming variations: Saʿd b. ʿUmārah, Saʿīd b. ʿUmārah, Saʿd b. ʿAmmār, and Saʿd b. ʿUbādah. Most authorities give the name as Saʿd b. ʿUmārah. Abū Nuʿaym lists his name as Saʿd b. ʿUmārah, and states that he was a companion, citing al-Bukhārī as his authority (NYMXV03P1281A). He differentiates Saʿd b. ʿUmārah, who was a member of the Saʿd b. Bakr tribe, from Saʿd b. ʿUmārah Abū Saʿīd al-Zaraqī al-Anṣārī. Ibn al-Athīr gives his name as Saʿd b. ʿUmārah al-Bakrī (THRXV02P448A). Ibn Ḥajar al-ʿAsqalānī gives his name as Saʿd b. ʿUmārah al-Thaʿlabī and refers to this tradition (without a witness) as one of those related on his authority. Ibn Ḥajar, however, differentiates between al-Thaʿlabī and Saʿd b. ʿUmārah who was a member of the Saʿd b. Bakr. He says that Ibn Isḥāq related information from both (HJRSV03P058B to HJRSV03P059A). Ibn Ḥajar adds to the confusion in the biography of Saʿd b. Bakr, whom he says is the brother of Saʿd b. ʿUmārah (HJRSV03P210C). He says Ibn Isḥāq mentioned traditions related by both. It is not clear if Ibn Ḥajar confuses the term “aḥad” (احد-one of) with the term “akhī” (اخي-brother of). In BKHBV04P044C, al-Bukhārī who gives the name as Saʿd b. ʿUbādah. Ibn Saʿd lists Saʿd b. ʿUbādah b. Dulaym b. Ḥārith b. Abī Ḥazīmah b. Thaʿlabah (which may be one of the sources of Ibn Ḥajar’s confusion). Ibn Saʿd, however, places him in the Sāʿidah b. Kaʿb b. al-Khazraj tribe. He was a Madīnan companion and a frequent source for Ibn Saʿd in his Ṭabaqāt (TKXXV03P460B). Saʿd b. ʿUbādah is mentioned in WZATB as a character in at least 20 passages, but not as an eyewitness source. He is also mentioned frequently in WSACD, WARMZ, WAIYA, WABAB, WHAYA, and WAANH as both a source and a character. @EC_01/07/23@

