# @HBHXV37P490A_BEG_WSACD
VAR_KTHJV04P109A حدثنا محمد بن عبيد حدثنا محمد بن إسحاق @TR2_YISI@ ويعقوب حدثنا @TR1_SACD@ أبي عن ابن إسحاق حدثني عباس بن سهل بن سعد عن أبيه قال قال رسول الله صلى الله عليه وسلم لعاصم بن عدي اقبضها إليك حتى تلد عندك فإن تلده أحمر فهو لأبيه الذي انتفى منه لعويمر وإن ولدته قطط الشعر أسود اللسان فهو لابن السحماء قال عاصم فلما وقع أخذته إلي فإذا رأسه مثل فروة الحمل الصغير ثم أخذت @TR2_YISI@ قال يعقوب بفقميه فإذا هو أحيمر مثل النبعة واستقبلني لسانه أسود مثل التمرة قال فقلت صدق الله ورسوله @HBHXV37P490A_END_WSACD 
PageV37P490
# @COMMENT: This passage is not found in the redaction of Ibn Hishām. KHGHV01P225A refers to this as the (قصة الملاعنة) "qiṣṣah al-malāʿanah" (the story of the calling down of the curse). In the well known story that refers to the revelation of Qurʾān 24:1-10 and the first instance of liʿān, a woman (sometimes identified as Khawlah bint Qays b. Muḥasin [HMMXV03P386A]), who had become pregnant, was accused of having ilicit sex, which she denied. Lacking four witnesses to the actual act, she vowed she was not guilty, and called curses down on herself if she was. The woman was married to the cousin of ʿĀsim b. ʿAdī (identified variously as Ḥilāl b. Umayyah [ANSSV06P172A] or ʿUwaymir al-Anṣārī [MSTMV05P145A], ʿUwaymir b. Ubayd (أبيض) al-Anṣārī al-ʿAjlānī, or ʿUwaymir b. al-Ḥārith b. Zayd b. Ḥārithah b. al-Jadd b. al-ʿAjlān [NWXXV02P041A] all of whom were members of the Banu al-ʿAjlān b. ʿAmr b. ʿAwf) and Muhammad advised ʿĀsim that the proof of the accusation would be the child's physical appearance (see MSTMV03P184A to MSTMV03P187A for an early detailed account). HBHXV37P490A identifies the accused man as Ibn al-Saḥmāʾ, whom MSTMV03P184A and ASUZV01P305A identifies as Sharīk b. al-Saḥmāʾ. According to JWTXV01P509A, al-Saḥmāʾ was Sharīk's mother, who was otherwise known as Umm al-Barrāʾ b. Mālik. Sharīk's father was ʿAbdah b. Muʿaṭṭib (JWTXV01P509A) or ʿAbdah b. Mughīth b. al-Jadd b. al-ʿAjlān (BRSXV02P821A). ʿAbdah b. Muʿaṭṭib, Sharīk, Umm al-Barrāʾ, and al-Barrāʾ b. Mālik are not mentioned in the redaction of Ibn Hishām. for a version via the witness of WYUAU, see KHGHV01P225A. 

