# @HBHXV32P210A_BEG_WSACD حدثنا @TR2_YISI@ يعقوب حدثنا @TR1_SACD@ أبي عن ابن إسحاق قال حدثني عبد الله بن أبي عاصم بن عروة بن مسعود الثقفي أن عمرو بن الشريد حدثه أن أباه حدثه أنه سمع رسول الله صلى الله عليه وسلم يقول إذا شرب الرجل فاجلدوه ثم إذا شرب فاجلدوه ثم إذا شرب فاجلدوه أربع مرار أو خمس مرار ثم إذا شرب فاقتلوه @HBHXV32P210A_END_WSACD 
PageV32P210 
# @COMMENT: HHMXV07P379A places this in the context of Ibn al-Nuʿmān and TKXXV03P375A quotes a portion of the passage in the biography of al-Nuʿmān b. ʿAmr (although he appears to suggest that Ibn Isḥāq names him as al-Nuʿaymān). TKXXV03P375A states that Nuʿaymān b. ʿAmr was the younger brother of Nuʿmān b. ʿAmr. Ibn al-Nuʿaymān or al-Nuʿaymān is not mentioned in the redaction of Ibn Hishām. He is sometimes identified as al-Nuʿaymān b. ʿAmr b. Rifāʿah b. al-Ḥārith. According to JWZXV05P277A, al-Nuʿaymān participated in Badr, and all of the famous battles in which Muḥammad fought. He was known to have repeatedly been punished for drinking nabīdh. BKHBV06P431A and TBRCV11P554A mention the account of ʿUqbah b. al-Ḥārith where he describes being ordered by Muḥammad to beat Ibn Nuʿaymān or al-Nuʿaymān with shoes and palm branches for drinking. TKXXV03P375A states he died in during the caliphate of Muʿawīyah but KTHBV08P070A places his death in the year 54. HJRSV06P353A states that Ibn Isḥāq identifies him as al-Nuʿmān b. ʿAmr and not as al-Nuʿaymān, this follows the comment of Ibn Hishām in vol. 1, 703A. A person identified as al-Nuʿmān b. ʿAmr is mention twice in the redaction of Ibn Hishām: on vol. 1, 552A he is identified as a Jew who was one of two Rabbis who questioned Muḥammad and then rejected him. On vol. 1, 703A he is identified as al-Nuʿmān b. ʿAmr b. Rifāʿah b. Sawād, a member of the Sawād b. Mālik b. Ghamm clan, among the Anṣ ār, who participated at Badr. Ibn Hishām, in his commentary, states his name was Nuʿaymān. It is not clear if Ibn Isḥāq understood al-Nuʿmān b. ʿAmr to be the individual who is commonly referred to as being punished for drinking. For passages within the Ibn Isḥāq tradition that identify Nuʿaymān or al-Nuʿaymān with the subject of the person punished for drinking, see via the witness of WZATB (but not found in the redaction of Ibn Hishām), NSKXV05P143A, NSSXV04P415A,IHMAV12P370A, BQRXV03P340A, BQSXV08P545A, BQMXV13P039A; via the witness of WYUAU, IBABV01P081A, BQSXV08P545A; via WSASN, IHMAV12P370A; without a witness, YNBHV12P358A. For another tradition via WAYSS regarding Nuʿaymān's role in the fever that struck Madīnah following the migration (the story is found in HSNXV01P588A to vol. 1, 590A without reference to Nuʿaymān), see STJXV07P031A, STBXV04P252A; without a witness, see HYMZV02P307A (quoting al-Ṭabarānī). For a tradition about the story of how Nuʿaymān killed the camel of a Beduoin, via WJHZA, see SBANV01P480A, QZHXV02P302A.

