### ||| سهيمة بنت عمير

# @BKHBV01P249C_BEG_WSACD
VAR_BKTMV01P552A VAR_YSSXV04P1866A VAR_KHLWV16P020E قال لي عبد العزيز بن عبد الله حدثنا عبد العزيز بن محمد عن يزيد بن الهاد عن محمد بن نافع بن عجير عن أبيه عن علي قال النبي صلى الله عليه وسلم PageV01P249 الخالة أم وقال لي علي حدثنا @TR2_YISI@ يعقوب بن إبراهيم قال حدثنا @TR1_SACD@ أبي عن ابن إسحاق قال حدثني محمد بن نافع بن عجير وكان ثقة سمع عبد الله بن الحارث بن عويمر المزني قال كان من النبي صلى الله عليه وسلم في عمتي سهيمة بنت عمير قضاء قضى به في امرأة قبلها وعن ابن إسحاق سمع محمد علي بن يزيد بن ركانة بن عبد يزيد سمع أباه قال طلق جدي ركانة سهيمة بنت عمير المزنية فردها عليه النبي صلى الله عليه وسلم مرسل @BKHBV01P249C_END_WSACD
PageV01P250
# @COMMENT: BKHBV01P249C is from the biography of Muḥammad b. Nāfiʿ b. ʿUjayr. The passage refers to Suhaymah bint ʿUmayr’s divorce from Rukānah b. ʿAbd Yazīd b. Hāshim. Rukānah is mentioned in HSNXV02P351A as receiving spoils from Khaybar. Suhaymah is not mentioned in the redaction of Ibn Hishām. The passage is Ibn Isḥāq’s assessment of Nāfiʿ b. ʿUjayr b. ʿAbd Yazīr b. Hāshim. The passage also refers to ʿAbd Allāh b. al-Ḥārith b. ʿUwaymir al-Muzanī. There are several women with the name Suhaymah bint ʿUmayr but with different kunyās, al-Anṣārīyah, al-Muzanīyah, and al-Shaybānīyah. In the story related via Ibn Isḥāq is about Suhaymah al-Muzanīyah, she is married to Rukānah b. ʿAbd Yazīd who announces three declarations of divorce against Suhaymah. The story is related to Ibn Isḥāq by Rukānah’s grandson, ʿAlī b. Yazīd b. Rukānah, or by Suhaymah’s nephew ʿAbd Allāh b. al-Ḥārith b. ʿUwaymir al-Muzanī, Rukānah seeks advice from the prophet about the manner of his divorce. It is clear from this story that it is set in the Madīnan period, although when is not clear. According to LFGHV01P420A, the dispute over Suhaymah al-Muzanīyah’s divorce lasted until after the death of Muḥammad and was brought before ʿUmar and ʿUthmān on five different occasions. This is also recounted by THRXV07P156A. Suhaymah bint ʿUmayr al-Anṣārīyah is described as the aunt of ʿAbd Allāh b. al-Ḥārith b. ʿUmayr by HJRSV08P194C. Ibn Ḥajar also provides a biographical entry for al-Muzanīyah on the same page, describing her as the wife of Rukānah. He provides different allusions to the divorce issue in both, without mentioning the husband’s name in the entry for al-Anṣārīyah, but saying that al-Muzanīyah took the issue to ʿUmar and ʿUthmān after Muḥammad’s death. This later source seems to separate elements of al-Muzanīyah’s story into one for al-Anṣārīyah, which is related by ʿAbd Allāh b. al-Ḥārith, while the al-Muzanīyah account is related by Nāfiʿ b. ʿUjayr, referenced by Ibn Isḥāq. Suhaymah bint ʿUmayr al-Shaybānīyah had a husband to went of to fight in the military campaigns and did not return. After waiting four years she remained. Shortly after her first husband returned during the Caliphate of ʿUthmān, both husbands traveled to see ʿUthmān to see how the situation should be resolved. He advised them that the first husband had the right to choose either to have his wife or her dowery. This occurred while ʿUthmān was besieged shortly before his death. Afterwards they turned to ʿAlī for advice, who reaffirmed ʿUthmān’s opinion. This story was related by Abū Mulayḥ b. Usāmah (see ADHDV09P695A). A version of this story is provided by THMIV02P331B (without a kunyā), also related by Abū Mulayḥ. The evidence suggests that the three people refer to a single individual whose story changed over time. It is not possible to know which version is earliest. Placement in the biography section is due to the present inability to place the text in the narrative.

